<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{hazuganai}}</strong> expresses the speaker's subjective judgement that an event is very unlikely.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{he^woman}}ga@KJ{{now^day}}no@KJ{{meeting^deliberation}}wo@KJ{{forget}}reru<strong>hazuhanai</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      It is unlikely that she will forget today's meeting.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{hazuganai}}</strong> is a phrase that expresses the speaker's opinion that "there is no reason why ...".

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kon'nakotowoshiteii<strong>wakeganai</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      No-one is allowed to do that kind of thing. (There is no reason why it is good to do such a thing.)
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{hazuganai}}</strong> can be used with sentences in the past. <strong>@HI{{wakeganai}}</strong> cannot be
used with past sentences, except indirectly by presenting the negation as a statement of common belief or about ability.
</p>

